In [[human anatomy]], the '''[[Adduction|adductor]] muscles of the [[hip]]''' are a group of [[human leg#Thigh|muscles of the thigh]].

==Muscles==
The adductor group is made up of:
*[[Adductor brevis muscle|Adductor brevis]]
*[[Adductor longus muscle|Adductor longus]]
*[[Adductor magnus muscle|Adductor magnus]]
*[[Adductor minimus muscle|Adductor minimus]] This is often considered to be a part of adductor magnus.
*[[Pectineus muscle|pectineus]]
*[[Gracilis muscle|gracilis]]
*[[Obturator externus muscle|Obturator externus]]<ref name="Platzer-240">Platzer, Werner (2004), ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=Bl8RO_Tq7zoC&pg=PA240" Color Atlas of Human Anatomy, Vol. 1, Locomotor System]'', Thieme, 5th ed, p 240</ref> and are also part of the [[medial compartment of thigh]]

==Origin and insertion==
The adductors originate on the [[Pubis (bone)|pubis]] and [[ischium]] bones and insert mainly on the medial posterior surface of the [[femur]].

